\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 .NET compiler warnings
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 ----------------------
\par 
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 The Delphi 7 dcc32 compiler now supports three
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 additional compiler warnings:  Unsafe_Type,
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 Unsafe_Code, and Unsafe_Cast.  These warnings are
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 disabled by default, but can be enabled with source
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 code compiler directives \{$WARN UNSAFE_CODE ON\},
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 compiler comma\hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 nd line switches (dcc32 -W+UNSAFE_CODE),
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 and in Project|Options.
\par 
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 NOTE: There is no space before or after the "+" in the
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2       command line switch)
\par 
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 "Unsafe" in all three messages refers to types or
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 operations which static code analysis cannot prove to
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 not\hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2  overwrite memory.  For example, data types that
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 carry bounds information at runtime such as Delphi
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 Strings or dynamic arrays can be bounds-checked at
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 runtime, and tracked in static analysis, to ensure that
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 memory accesses are within the limits of the allo\hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 cated
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 data.  Data types that do not carry bounds information
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 at compile time or runtime (such as PChar) cannot be
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 proven safe.  Unsafe doesn't necessarily mean the code
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 is broken or flawed, it simply means that it uses
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 programming techniques that cannot be\hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2  verified as safe
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 by static code analysis.  In a secured execution
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 environment such as .NET, such code is assumed to be
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 unsafe and a potential security risk.
\par 
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 Delphi 7 developers can use these new warnings to
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 identify data types, code or programming techniques
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 that may be difficult to port to a managed code
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 environment such as .NET.  These messages are not
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 specific to the .NET platform.  The warnings are
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 conservative - some things we warn about in D7 we might
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 a\hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 ctually be able to support in Delphi for .NET, but
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 we're not sure yet.  The warnings are not complete -
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 there may be problematic types or code situations for
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 which the Delphi 7 compiler does not issue an unsafe
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 warning.
\par 
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 Unsafe_Type:  Types such as PChar, \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 untyped pointer,
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 untyped var and out parameters, file of <type>, 6 byte
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 reals (Real48), variant records (records containing
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 overlapping fields) and old-style objects
\par 
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 ("TMyObject = object").
\par 
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2   * "old" object type
\par 
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2        c = object
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2          i: Integer;
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2   \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2        procedure p;
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2        end;
\par 
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 Unsafe_Code:  absolute variables, Addr(), Ptr(), Hi(),
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 Lo(), Swap() standard procedures, BlockRead and
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 BlockWrite, the Fail() standard procedure, GetMem(),
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 FreeMem(), and ReallocMem()
\par 
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2   * inline assembler blocks (asm end)
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2   * @ operator
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2   * modifying string index elements, e.g
\par 
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2       s := 'Hoho';
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2       s[2] := 'a'; // <-- "Unsafe code 'String index to
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2       var param'"
\par 
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 Unsafe_Cast:  Casting an object instance to a type that
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 is not an ancestor or descendent of the instance \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 type,
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 casting a record type to anything else
\par 
