\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 dbExpress MSSQL driver BLOB access
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 -----------------------------------
\par 
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 dbExpress MSSQL uses ISeque\hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 ntialStream (OLEDB
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 interface) to access blobs from SQL Server. MS OLEDB
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 provider (SQLOLEDB) doesn't support accessing more than
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 one in a SELECT using ISequentialStream. So, if you are
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 projecting more than one blob column in your queries
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 the dbExpress drive\hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 r will not use the ISequentialStream
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 to access blobs. Instead, it will bind huge buffers to
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 get the blob data. The buffer size is determined by the
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 BlobSize entry in dbxconnections.ini. Make sure to set
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 it to an appropriate size to improve performance when
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 more than one blob column is projected.
\par 
\par 
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 MySQL limitation (dbExpress)
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 ----------------------------
\par 
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 MySQL can't filter with FLOAT fields in the WHERE
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 clause. Since this limitation prevents updates with
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 TClientDataset and TDataSetProvider, use DOUBLE
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 instead. For more information, see the MySQL
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 documentation.
\par 
\par 
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 Huge Text in MySQL (dbExpress)
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 ------------------------------
\par 
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af23\loch\f2 MySQL Server has a startup parameter called max-
